T1  - Order imbalance, liquidity, and market returns
AU  - Chordia, Tarun
AU  - Roll, Richard
AU  - Subrahmanyam, Avanidhar
JO  - Journal of Financial Economics
VL  - 65
IS  - 1
SP  - 111
EP  - 130
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/07/01/
SN  - 0304-405X
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0304-405X(02)00136-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304405X02001368
KW  - Liquidity
KW  - Trading volume
KW  - Order imbalance
AB  - Traditionally, volume has provided the link between trading activity and returns. We focus on a hitherto unexplored but intuitive measure of trading activity: the aggregate daily order imbalance, buy orders less sell orders, on the New York Stock Exchange. Order imbalance increases following market declines and vice versa, which reveals that investors are contrarians on aggregate. Order imbalances in either direction, excess buy or sell orders, reduce liquidity. Market-wide returns are strongly affected by contemporaneous and lagged order imbalances. Market returns reverse themselves after high-negative-imbalance, large-negative-return days. Even after controlling for aggregate volume and liquidity, market returns are affected by order imbalance.
